Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
editDeselect(25.10)                                        editDeselect(25.10)

Name
       editDeselect - Deselects wires and vias based on specified parameters

Syntax
       editDeselect

       [-help]

       [-area {<x1><y1><x2><y2>}]

       [-direction {H | V | 45 | 135}]

       [-floating_via]

       [-layer <list_of_layers>]

       [-nets <net>*]

       [-physical_pin_only]

       [-regular_wire_with_drc]

       [-shape {RING STRIPE FOLLOWPIN IOWIRE COREWIRE BLOCKWIRE PADRING

                BLOCKRING FILLWIRE FILLWIREOPC DRCFILL None}]

       [-shield]

       [-shield_only]

       [-status {COVER FIXED NOSHIELD ROUTED SHIELD UNKNOWN}]

       [-subclass <sublass_name>]

       [-type {Regular Special Patch}]

       [-use {CLOCK POWER SIGNAL}]

       [-via_cell <cell_name_list>]

       [-with_edit_flag {0 | 1}]

       [-object_type {Wire Via} ]

       [-from_pin <pin_name> -to_pin <pin_name>]

       Deselects  wires  and vias based on specified parameters. Use this com-
       mand when nets are selected.

       You can use this command to deselect nets by property. For example,  to
       delete all regular nets except clock nets, select all regular nets with
       editSelect,  deselect the clock nets with this command, then delete the
       selected nets with editDelete.

Parameters
       -help  Prints a brief description that includes type and default infor-
              mation for each editDeselect parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man editDeselect

       -area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}
              Specifies the coordinates for the area from  which  to  deselect
              wires and vias.

       -direction {H | V | 45 | 135}
              Specifies the orientation of the wires to deselect.

              Default:  If  you do not specify this parameter, deselects wires
              in any orientation.

              *

                H: Specifies that horizontal wires are to be deselected.

              *

                V: Specifies that vertical wires are to be deselected.

              * 45: Specifies that 45-degree wires are to be deselected.

              * 135: Specifies that 135-degree wires are to be deselected.

       -floating_via
              Specifies that only floating vias are to be deselected.  A  via,
              or  a  stack of vias, is floating, if it is not connected to an-
              other object, wire, pin, or via, on either  its  top  or  bottom
              metal layer or on both these layers.

       -from_pin <pin_name>
              Specifies  the  name of the starting pin of the wire to be dese-
              lected.

              The starting pin you specify should be connected to the same net
              as the ending pin specified with -to_pin.  If  they  connect  to
              different nets, the tool reports an error.

              Note:  Deselection  of wires between specified pins is supported
              only for signal and clock nets.

       -layer <list_of_layers>
              Specifies the layers from which to deselect wires and vias. This
              option supports backside and Through Silicon Via (TSV) layers as
              well.

              If you are specifying multiple  layers,  enclose  the  names  in
              braces.

              Default:  If  you do not specify this parameter, deselects wires
              and vias from all layers.

       -nets <net>*
              Specifies the net names from which to deselect wires and vias.

              Note: You can use wildcard values in this field. For example, if
              you specify V*, deselects wires and vias from nets VDD and VSS.

       -object_type {Wire Via}
              Specifies whether wires or vias or both should be deselected. If
              the parameter is not specified, only wires are deselected.

              Default: Wire

       -physical_pin_only
              Specifies that physical pins are to be deselected.  By  default,
              editDeselect does not deselect physical pins.

              You  can  use the -physical_pin_only parameter along with -area,
              -layer, or -nets to deselect the physical pins in the  specified
              area, layer, or net, respectively.

       -regular_wire_with_drc
              Deselects regular wires with violation markers.

       -shape {RING STRIPE FOLLOWPIN IOWIRE COREWIRE BLOCKWIRE PADRING BLOCK-
       RING FILLWIRE FILLWIREOPC DRCFILL None}
              Specifies the shapes of the wires and vias to be deselected. Use
              all  upper-case  letters for the shapes. If you specify multiple
              shapes, enclose the list of shapes in braces. For shape  defini-
              tions,  see  Shapes,  in the "DEF Syntax" chapter of the LEF/DEF
              Language Reference.

              Default: If you do not specify this parameter,  deselects  wires
              and vias of all shapes.

       -shield
              Deselects  the  wires  and  vias  of the nets specified with the
              -nets parameter, along with the wires  and  vias  shielding  the
              specified nets.

              Note: This parameter cannot be used with -shield_only.

       -shield_only
              Deselects  only the shield wires associated with the nets speci-
              fied using the -nets parameter. The signal nets  being  shielded
              remain selected.

              Note: This parameter cannot be used with -shield.

       -status {COVER FIXED NOSHIELD ROUTED SHIELD UNKNOWN}
              Specifies the status of the wires and vias to be deselected. Use
              all  upper-case letters for the status. If you specify more than
              one status, enclose the status list in curly braces.

              Note: If you select -type Special -status NOSHIELD or -type Sig-
              nal -status SHIELD the software generates an error message.

       -subclass <sublass_name>
              Specifies the subclass name of the wires and vias  to  be  dese-
              lected. Use this parameter if you want to deselect wires or vias
              belonging  to  a  specific  subclass. Here, <subclass_name> is a
              user-defined attribute that has been  previously  defined  using
              the  -uda parameter of the addSplitPowerVia, addRing, addStripe,
              or sroute command.

              For wires, use this parameter if you want to deselect or  delete
              rings, stripes, or other wires belonging to a specific subclass.
              Only special wire is supported by this option.

              Note: You can use wildcards in <subclass_name>.

       -to_pin <pin_name>
              Specifies  the  name  of  the ending pin of the wire to be dese-
              lected.

              The ending pin you specify should be connected to the  same  net
              as the starting pin specified with -from_pin. If they connect to
              different nets, the tool reports an error. In addition, the from
              and to pins you specify should be connected to the same wire. If
              there  there are more than one wire or via between the specified
              starting and ending pins, the command is not  able  to  deselect
              the wire path and returns an error.

              The  -from_pin  and  -to_pin parameters are compatible with only
              the -direction, -layer, -object_type, and -status options of the
              editDeselect command. If you use -from_pin and -to_pin with  any
              other editDeselect parameters, the tool returns an error.

              Note:  Deselection  of wires between specified pins is supported
              only for signal and clock nets.

       -type {Regular Special Patch}
              Specifies whether to deselect regular wires  and  vias,  special
              wires and vias, or patch wires.

              Note: If you specify Regular, you must omit the -shape parameter
              or specify -shape None.

       -use {CLOCK POWER SIGNAL}
              Specifies  whether  to  deselect  only  CLOCK  wires/vias, POWER
              wires, or SIGNAL wires.

       -via_cell <cell_name_list>
              Specifies the via cells of the vias to be  deselected.  You  can
              use wildcards while specifying via cell names. If you are speci-
              fying multiple cell names, enclose them in braces.

       -with_edit_flag {0 | 1}
              Deselects  all  modified  wires and vias, that is wires and vias
              with value 1 for the isEdit property on the net.

              Notes

              * As the isEdit property is added on  the  whole  net,  all  the
                wires  and  vias on the net with isEdit value set to 1 will be
                deselected.

              * The isEdit property is used to flag nets with  modified  wires
                and vias. This is useful when evaluating how many objects need
                to  be  modified  for  fixing DRC violations and then deciding
                whether to fix the violations manually or through ECO routing.
                The  isEdit  property  is   controlled   through   the   -cre-
                ate_is_edit_flag  parameter  of  setEditMode. By default, this
                parameter is set to 0. If you set the value of this  parameter
                to  1,  the isEdit property is set to 1 for nets with modified
                wires or vias.

Examples
              * The following command deselects all  horizontal  fillwires  on
                the METAL1 layer:

                editDeselect -layers METAL1 -direction H -shape FILLWIRE

              * The following command deselects all vias:

                editDeselect -object_type Via

              * The following command deselects all wires:

                editDeselect

              * The following command deselects all wires and vias:

                editDeselect -object_type {Wire Via}

